{{For|disambiguation|Bagadi (disambiguation){{!}}Bagadi}}
The '''Bagdis''' are [[Indigenous peoples|indigenous people]] descended from people with [[Dravidian peoples|Dravidian]] links found in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]] and  [[Bangladesh]]. The Bagdis are populous in [[Bankura district|Bankura]], [[Birbhum district|Birbhum]] and other districts in the western fringe of West Bengal. They speak [[Bengali language|Bengali]].<ref name=banglapedia>{{cite book |last=Rahman |first=S M Mahfuzur |year=2012 |chapter=Bagdi |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Bagdi |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>

The Bagdis numbered 2,740,385  in West Bengal in the 2001 Indian census and were 14.9 per cent of the [[Scheduled castes and scheduled tribes|scheduled caste]] population of West Bengal.  47.7 per cent of the Bagdis were literate –  60.4 per cent males and 34.8 per cent females were literate.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/dh_sc_westbengal.pdf| title = West Bengal, Census of India 2001, Data Highlights – The Scheduled Castes| accessdate = 2009-06-28 | last =  | first =  | work = | publisher = Office of the Registrar General, India }}</ref>

The Bagdis were one of the most prominent warrior clans in old India. During the British rule in India, many bands of Bagdis were involved in criminal activities and as a result, they were declared as criminal tribes by the British.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.boloji.com/analysis/011.htm| title = Robbery  | accessdate = 2009-06-29 | last =  | first =   | work = | publisher = boloji}}</ref>

