{{Infobox language |name=Minica Huitoto |nativename=''Mɨnɨka'' |states=[[Colombia]], [[Perú]] |speakers=6,800 |date=2002 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Bora–Witoto languages|Bora–Witoto]] |fam2=[[Witoto–Ocaina languages|Witoto–Ocaina]] |fam3=[[Witoto languages|Witoto]] |fam4=Minica–Murui |iso3=hto |glotto=mini1256 |glottorefname=Minica Huitoto }}
'''Minica''' (Mɨnɨka) '''Huitoto''' is one of three indigenous American Huitoto languages of the Witotoan family spoken by a few thousand speakers in western South America.<ref name="ethnologue.com">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=hto Ethnologue report for language code:hto<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
It is spoken in the Upper Igara-Paraná river area, along the Caquetá River at the Isla de los Monos, and the Caguán River near San Vicente del Caguán. There is 75% literacy in Colombia and 85% are literate in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]; most are bilingual. There is a dictionary and grammar rules.<ref name="ethnologue.com"/>
There are only five speakers in [[Perú]], where it has official standing within its community.<ref name="ethnologue.com"/>
