==Language==
The language of the Tsimihety people is a dialect of the [[Malagasy language]],<ref name=brittsim/> a branch of the [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian language group]] derived from the [[Barito languages]] spoken in the [[Austronesia]]n region.<ref>[https://www.ethnologue.com/language/xmw Malagasy, Tsimihety], Ethnologue</ref><ref>Dm Albro (2005), [http://glottolog.org/resource/languoid/id/tsim1257 Language: Tsimihety Malagasy], Max Planck Institute for the Science of Human History</ref>

==Economy==
Tsimihety society and economy, as in much of [[Madagascar]], is primarily focused on agriculture. Rice is the staple crop, and the Tsimihety raise cattle.<ref name=brittsim/> Working on crop land on Tuesday is [[Fady (taboo)|fady]] – a taboo – among the Tsimihety.{{sfn|Bradt|2007|p=14}} The main economic center among the Tsimihety is in Mandritsara.{{sfn|Bradt|2007|p=424}}

