{{Infobox Ethnic group |group = Yudjá |image= |caption= |population = 348 (2010)<ref name=intro>[http://pib.socioambiental.org/en/povo/yudja "Yudjá: Introduction."] ''Instituto Socioambiental: Povos Indígenas no Brasil.'' Retrieved 26 March 2012</ref> |popplace = {{Flag|Brazil}} ({{Flag|Mato Grosso}}) |languages = [[Yudjá language|Yudjá]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]<ref name=ethno>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=jur "Jurúna."] ''Ethnologue.'' 2009. Retrieved 26 March 2012.</ref> |religions = traditional tribal religion<ref>[http://pib.socioambiental.org/en/povo/yudja/647 "Yudjá: Cosmology e Shamanism."] ''Instituto Socioambiental: Povos Indígenas no Brasil.'' Retrieved 26 March 2012</ref> |related = }}
The '''Yudjá''' are an [[Indigenous people of Brazil]], who live in the states of [[Mato Grosso]] and [[Pará]]. They live in two villages in the [[Xingu Indigenous Park]], located near the mouth of the [[Maritsauá-Mitau River]]. They fish and raise crops, such as [[manioc]].<ref name=ethno/>
==Name== The Yudjá are also known as the Iuruna, Jaruna, Yudya, Yurúna,<ref name=ethno/> Juruna, Yuruna,<ref name=intro/> Juruhuna, Jurûna, and Geruna people.
==Population== In 2011, the Yudjá population is 348.<ref name=intro/> Their population was 278 in 2001,<ref name=ethno/> up from a low of 37 in 1950.
==Language== The [[Yudjá language|Yudjá]] or [[Jurúna language]] belongs to the [[Yurúna language]] family, one of the [[Tupian languages]].<ref name=ethno/>
